The Voice is an American reality television singing competition broadcast on NBC and produced by Talpa Media USA, Inc.. Created by John de Mol, the series premiered on April 26, 2011. Based on the original The Voice of Holland, and part of The Voice franchise it has aired ten seasons and aims to find currently unsigned singing talent (solo or duets, professional and amateur) contested by aspiring singers, age 13 or over, drawn from public auditions.
The winner is determined by television viewers voting by telephone, Internet, SMS text, and iTunes Store purchases of the audio-recorded artists' vocal performances. They receive US$100,000 and a record deal with Universal Music Group for winning the competition. The winners of the ten seasons have been Javier Colon, Jermaine Paul, Cassadee Pope, Danielle Bradbery, Tessanne Chin, Josh Kaufman, Craig Wayne Boyd, Sawyer Fredericks, Jordan Smith, and Chris Blue.
The series employs a panel of four coaches who critique the artists' performances and guide their teams of selected artists through the remainder of the season. They also compete to ensure that their act wins the competition, thus making them the winning coach. The original panel consisted of Christina Aguilera, CeeLo Green, Adam Levine, and Blake Shelton, all vocalists who have been part of the music industry. The series has also been joined by hosts Carson Daly and Christina Milian, who announce the name of a winning artist from each team and the results of international text voting. The fourth season of the series premiered on March 25, 2013.

The book is divided into five chapters, each of which contains a separate poem. The first four chapters are written in the form of acrostic poems, where each verse begins with a successive letter of the Hebrew alphabet. The fifth chapter is written in the form of a dirge, a lamentation in the form of a song.
The book of Lamentations is a powerful and emotional expression of grief and mourning for the loss of Jerusalem and the Temple. It is believed to have been written in the aftermath of the destruction of Jerusalem and the Temple, and it serves as a reminder of the importance of repentance and the need for forgiveness.
The book of Lamentations is a reminder of the power of God and His ability to bring about redemption and restoration, even in the face of great suffering and loss. 2013年2月20日に、スタジアムの名前は「University of Phoenix Stadium」から「Glendale Stadium」に変更されることが発表された。 2013年2月20日、Glendale City Councilは、University of Phoenixの契約を終了し、Glendale Stadiumを新たな契約で命名することを決定した。 これにより、2013年2月20日、University of Phoenix StadiumはGlendale Stadiumに名前を変更された。 Glendale Stadiumは、NFLのアリゾナ・カージナルスとNCAAのアリゾナ大学のホームスタジアムである。
Glendale Stadium is a multi-purpose stadium in Glendale, Arizona, a suburb of Phoenix. Completed in 2006, at a cost of $455 million, it is part of the Westgate Entertainment District and is located next to the Peoria Sports Complex and the Tanger Outlets. The stadium serves as the home of the Arizona Cardinals of the National Football League (NFL) and the Arizona Rattlers of the Indoor Football League (IFL). The stadium is named for its primary tenant, the University of Phoenix, an online university.
The stadium is the first retractable-roof NFL stadium and was the 44th largest stadium in college football and the 46th largest NFL stadium by official seating capacity as of 2013. The stadium has hosted two Super Bowls, XLII in 2008 and XLIX in 2015. It has also hosted college football bowl games, college basketball, the 2007 NFL Draft, the 2011 CONCACAF Gold Cup final, and concerts. The stadium has hosted the Fiesta Bowl since 2007 and the Arizona Bowl since 2015.

The Amazing World of Gumball (2011-2019) is an animated series created by Ben Bocquelet for Cartoon Network.
The series follows the life of Gumball Watterson, a 12-year old cat who attends middle school in Elmore. Accompanied by his pet, adoptive brother, and best friend Darwin, he frequently finds himself involved in various shenanigans around town and at school, during which he interacts with the other main characters: Anais, his younger sister; Nicole, their mother; and Richard, their father and the principal of Elmore Junior High, where Gumball and Darwin attend. The series also features a large ensemble of supporting students and teachers appearing alongside Gumball and Darwin.
The series premiered on May 3, 2011 and is currently airing its sixth season. The series is produced by Cartoon Network Development Studio Europe and Boulder Media Limited. It is distributed by Turner Broadcasting System Europe.

When was the Samsung Galaxy S6 Edge released?
The Samsung Galaxy S6 Edge was released on April 10, 2015.
The Samsung Galaxy S6 Edge is an Android smartphone produced by Samsung Electronics. It was unveiled on March 1, 2015, at Mobile World Congress in Barcelona, Spain, and was released on April 10, 2015, in 20 countries, as the immediate successor to the Galaxy S5. The S6 Edge is the first smartphone to use a dual-edge screen, a feature that was later used in the Samsung Galaxy Note Edge, the Samsung Galaxy S7 Edge, and the Samsung Galaxy Note 7.

The American Revolutionary War (1775–1783), also known as the American War of Independence, was a global war that began as a conflict between Great Britain and its Thirteen Colonies which declared independence as the United States of America. After 1765, growing philosophical and political differences strained the relationship between Great Britain and its colonies. Patriot protests against taxation without representation followed the Stamp Act and escalated into boycotts, which culminated in 1773 with the Sons of Liberty destroying a shipment of tea in Boston Harbor. Britain responded by closing Boston Harbor and passing a series of punitive measures against Massachusetts Bay Colony. Massachusetts colonists responded with the Suffolk Resolves, and they established a shadow government which wrested control of the countryside from the Crown. Twelve colonies formed a Continental Congress to coordinate their resistance, establishing committees and conventions that effectively seized power. British attempts to disarm the Massachusetts militia in Concord led to open combat on April 19, 1775. Militia forces then besieged Boston, forcing a British evacuation in March 1776, and Congress appointed George Washington to command the Continental Army. Concurrently, an American attempt to invade Quebec and raise rebellion against the British failed decisively. On July 2, 1776, the Continental Congress voted for independence, issuing its declaration on July 4. Sir William Howe launched a British counter-offensive, capturing New York City and leaving American morale at a low ebb. However, victories at Trenton and Princeton restored American confidence. In 1777, the British launched an invasion from Quebec under John Burgoyne, intending to isolate the New England Colonies. Instead of assisting this effort, Howe took his army on a separate campaign against Philadelphia, and Burgoyne was decisively defeated at Saratoga in October 1777. Burgoyne's defeat had drastic consequences. France formally allied with the Americans and entered the war in 1778, and Spain joined the war the following year as an ally of France but not as an ally of the United States. In 1780, the Kingdom of Mysore attacked the British in India, and tensions between Great Britain and the Netherlands erupted into open war. In North America, the British mounted a "Southern strategy" led by Charles Cornwallis which hinged upon a Loyalist uprising, but too few came forward. Cornwallis suffered reversals at King's Mountain and Cowpens. He retreated to Yorktown, Virginia, intending an evacuation, but a decisive French naval victory deprived him of an escape. A Franco-American army led by the Comte de Rochambeau and Washington then besieged Cornwallis' army and, with no sign of relief, he surrendered in October 1781. Whigs in Britain had long opposed the pro-war Tories in Parliament, and the surrender gave them the upper hand. In early 1782, Parliament voted to end all offensive operations in America, but the war continued overseas. Britain remained under siege in Gibraltar but scored a major victory over the French navy. On September 3, 1783, the belligerent parties signed the Treaty of Paris in which Great Britain agreed to recognize the sovereignty of the United States and formally end the war. French involvement had proven decisive, but France made few gains and incurred crippling debts. Spain made some territorial gains but failed in its primary aim of recovering Gibraltar. The Dutch were defeated on all counts and were compelled to cede territory to Great Britain. In India, the war against Mysore and its allies concluded in 1784 without any territorial changes.

The Platters were a popular American vocal group of the early rock and roll era. Their distinctive sound was a bridge between the pre-rock Tin Pan Alley tradition, and the burgeoning new genre. The original lineup consisted of lead tenor Tony Williams, David Lynch, Paul Robi, Herb Reed, and Zola Taylor. With the addition of Tony Williams, the group was formed in 1952 in Los Angeles, California, United States. In 1954, Williams and the group were signed onto a recording contract with Federal Records, a subsidiary of Cincinnati-based King Records. Their first hit was the ballad "Only You (And You Alone)" which was released in 1955, and went to number one on the R&B chart and number five on the pop chart. The group's second hit was "The Great Pretender", released in 1956, which was their first number one pop hit and went to number four on the R&B chart. The Platters had 12 songs that reached the Top 30 on the pop charts, including four additional Top Ten hits: "My Prayer", "Smoke Gets in Your Eyes", "Twilight Time", and "Harbor Lights". The Platters were the most successful vocal group of the early rock and roll era. Their style was an unusually smooth mix of doo-wop and R&B, and their arranger, Tony Williams, was a major innovator in developing the lush, sophisticated orchestrations that characterized the group's recordings. They were the first black vocal group to reach a mainstream audience; their music filled a void left by the passing of swing music and the rise of rock 'n' roll. The group was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 1990. In 1998, they were ranked number 58 on VH1's 100 Greatest Artists of Rock 'n' Roll.
